The people of Macedonia decided in a referendum on Sunday whether their name would change to "Republic of North Macedonia," a gesture that would resolve a decades-long conflict with Greece, which had blocked its bid for membership of the European Union and NATO.
Greece, which has a province called Macedonia, maintains that the name of its northern neighbor is a claim to its territory and has vetoed its entry into NATO and the EU.
In June, both governments reached an agreement on the proposed new name, but nationalist opponents argue that the change would undermine the ethnic identity of the Slav population, mostly in Macedonia.
President Gjorge Ivanov has said he will not vote in the referendum and a boycott campaign has questioned whether participation will reach the minimum 50 percent required for the referendum to be considered valid.
The referendum ballot asked the following question: "Are you in favour of joining NATO and the EU with the acceptance of the agreement with Greece?"
Supporters of the name change, including Prime Minister Zoran Zaev, argue that it is a price worth paying for Macedonia, one of the countries emerging from the disintegration of Yugoslavia, to try to access bodies like the EU and NATO.
"Today I came to vote for the future of the country, for the young people of Macedonia, so that they can live freely under the protection of the European Union, because this means a safer life for all," said Olivera Georgijevska, 79, in Skopje.
Although it will not be legally binding, many Members of Parliament have said that they will respect the result of the vote to make it decisive.
The change of name requires a two-thirds majority in Parliament.
The State Electoral Commission stated that, at one o'clock in the afternoon, no irregularities had been reported.
However, turnout was only 16%, compared to 34% in the last parliamentary elections held in 2016, when 66% of registered voters cast their vote.
“I have come to vote for my children, our place is in Europe,” said Gjose Tanevski, 62, who was voting in the capital, Skopje.
Macedonian Prime Minister Zoran Zaev, his wife Zorica and son Dushko cast their vote in the Macedonian referendum on a name change of the country that would open the avenues for joining NATO and the European Union in Strumica (Macedonia) on September 30, 2018.
In front of parliament in Skopje, Vladimir Kavardarkov, 54, was preparing a small stage and removing chairs in front of tents planted by those who were going to boycott the referendum.
“We are in favor of joining NATO and the EU, but we want to do it with our heads high, not through the back door,” Kavadarkov said.
“We are a poor country, but we have dignity.
If they don’t want us to enter as Macedonia, we can establish relations with other countries, such as China and Russia, and be part of Eurasian integration.”
Prime Minister Zaev says NATO membership would bring the much-needed investment Macedonia, whose unemployment rate is over 20%.
“I think the vast majority will be in favour, as more than 80 percent of citizens are in favour of the EU and NATO,” Zaev said after casting his vote.
He said a positive outcome would be a “confirmation of our future.”
In a poll published last Monday by the Institute for Policy Research it was assured that between 30 and 43% of the voters would participate in the referendum, which is a participation less than the required.
Another survey conducted by Telma TV of Macedonia revealed that 57% of respondents planned to vote on Sunday.
Of these, 70 per cent said they would vote in favour.
For the referendum to be considered a success, the turnout must be 50% plus one vote.
Should it fail, it would be the first serious blow to the pro-Western government’s policy since it came to power in May last year.
