Tim Berners-Lee, the inventor of the World Wide Web, is launching a new company that is trying to rival Facebook, Amazon and Google.
Inrupt is the latest project in the technology legend. A company that builds on Berners-Lee’s open source platform Solid.
Solid allows users to choose where to store their data and who will have access to what information.
In an exclusive interview with Fast Company, Berners-Lee joked that the intention behind Inrupt is to "dominate the world."
“It has to be now,” he said of the startup.
“It’s a historic moment.”
The app uses Solid’s technology so users can create their own “online personal data storage” or a POD.
It can contain lists, to-do lists, calendar, music library, and other personal and professional tools.
It’s as if Google Drive, Microsoft Outlook, Slack and Spotify are all available in one browser at the same time.
One thing that is unique in storing personal online data is that the user is the one who completely decides who can access what kind of information.
The company calls it “personal training through data.”
Inrupt’s idea, according to the company’s CEO, John Bruce, is to incorporate resources, processes and skills necessary for Solid to reach everyone.
At the moment, the company consists of Berners-Lee, Bruce, a security platform that IBM bought, some of the staffed developers who were hired to work on the project, and a community of volunteer programmers.
Starting this week, technology developers around the world could create their own decentralized apps with the tools available on the Inrupt website.
Berners-Lee said he and his team are not talking to "Facebook and Google about whether or not a radical change is going to be introduced where all their business models are completely modified overnight.
"We're not going to ask for permission."
In a post on Medium on Saturday, Berners-Lee wrote about Inrupt that “its mission is to provide commercial power and an ecosystem to help protect the integrity and quality of the new web created on Solid.”
In 1994, Berners-Lee transformed the Internet when he founded the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C) at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
In recent months, Berners-Lee has played a very influential role in the net neutrality debate.
Despite even launching Inrupt, Berners-Lee will remain the founder and director of the World Wide Web Consortium, the Web Foundation and the Open Data Institute.
“I’m incredibly optimistic about this next era of the web,” added Berners-Lee.
