Red Tide Update: Concentrations in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota Decreased
The new report by the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission shows an overall reduction in red tide concentrations in areas of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC, irregular flowering conditions are being reported in areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties, suggesting a reduction in concentrations.
Red tide flowering extends approximately 130 miles of coastline from Pinellas County to the north to Lee County to the south.
Irregular plots can be found about 10 miles off the coast of Hillsborough County, but in fewer places compared to last week.
Red tide has also been detected in Pasco County.
During the past week, there have been reported average concentrations in Pinellas County and its coast, low to high concentrations in Hillsborough County's coast, background to high concentrations in Manatee County, background to high concentrations in Sarasota County and its coast, background to high concentrations in Sarasota County and its coast, background to high concentrations in Charlotte County and its coast.
Respiratory irritation problems continue to be reported in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties.
No respiratory irritation problems have been reported in the Northwest Florida area during the past week.
